        "id": 3010526,
        "name": "Mark Golodetz",
        "username": "Mark_Golodetz",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/mark_golodetz/{size}/76850_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-10-25T13:47:29.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Opened and decanted a couple of hours before serving, but the nose was lovely as I decanted. The wine is harder than most 1982s, and the tannins which were originally quite angular have softened but not completely. It takes away some of the prettiness of most 1982s, which are almost all seamless, but I like the slight edginess.</p>\n<p>The wine is incredibly aromatic, with reddish fruit, anise, spices and leather. There is a little bit of the roses which I associate with Calon on the nose, but it is much more dominant in the mouth. The finish still has the edginess, but it is long and complex. A very good wine, but atypical for the vintage. Very Calon, very much to my taste. No rush to drink.  Somewhere around 94 points.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 8,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T22:55:13.923Z",
